The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, Nov. 28: The Centre and Saudi Arabia have made it mandatory for Haj pilgrims to have the polio vaccine before leaving the country. 

 There would be vaccine camps at Dum Dum airport, minorities development minister Abdus Sattar said. 

 Calcutta: The Calcu- tta Municipal Corpora-tion (Amendment) Bill, 2006, was passed amid protests from Opposi- tion leaders who said it would lead to a property tax hike. It calls for a change in the valuation procedure. The muni- cipal affairs minister said the highest tax has come down from 40 to 20 per cent of the value of property and the lowest from 11 to 6 per cent.

 Calcutta: At least four people were injured when a truck hit a bus returning from a wed- ding reception on Mayo Road late on Tuesday night. 

 Islampur: Congress MLA Deepa Das Munshis car was attacked on Tuesday. Deepa, wife of Union minister Priya Ranjan, was here to campaign for the December 4 bypoll. The windshield of the car was smashed. One of them also fired in the air, she said. 

 Calcutta: The finance minister chaired a meeting of secretaries to find ways to ensure speedy clearance for industrial units. All departments will submit details of clearances issued and they would be discussed.

 Calcutta: Trinamul MLA Sonali Guha told the Assembly on Tues- day that women from Singur will shed clothes in protest against land acquisition. 




